        </div>

        <p class="mt-6 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">The three essential features — scheduled runs, historical data retention, and multi-platform coverage — are non-negotiable for a tracking tool. A platform that requires manual triggering, does not store history, or only covers one AI platform is a checker with a recurring-subscription wrapper, not a tracker. Verify all three before committing to any paid plan.</p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Alert functionality and competitive benchmarking become increasingly important as your programme scales. In the early stages, you may review data manually each week. As query libraries grow and the number of tracked competitors increases, manual review becomes impractical. Tools with well-designed alert systems let you focus attention on what has actually changed rather than reviewing everything every cycle.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="tracking-workflow">
        <h2 class="anchor-top">How to Build a GEO Tracking Workflow</h2>
        <p><strong>A GEO tracking workflow is the repeating process that connects your measurement infrastructure to your optimisation decisions — without a defined workflow, tracking data accumulates without producing action.</strong></p>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-5">
