          <p class="text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed">Pricing, feature sets, platform coverage, and company status in this category change rapidly. Always test a tool against your specific query library and use case before committing. For current, unbiased recommendations matched to your programme stage and budget, <a href="/contact/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">contact our team</a> — we evaluate GEO tooling continuously as part of our advisory practice. See also the broader <a href="/geo-tools/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO tools guide</a> for the full tool ecosystem context.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="interpreting-data">
        <h2 class="anchor-top">Interpreting Your GEO Tracking Data</h2>
        <p><strong>Raw citation frequency numbers are only useful when interpreted in context — the same 25% citation rate can represent strong performance for a new brand entering a crowded category or a concerning decline for an established brand that was previously at 40%.</strong></p>
        <p>Always interpret tracking data relative to three reference points: your own baseline (where you started), your trend direction (which way you are moving), and your competitive position (how your citation frequency compares to named competitors for the same query set). A declining trend that is still above competitors warrants less urgent action than a declining trend combined with rising competitor citation rates for the same queries.</p>
        <p>Platform variation deserves particular attention. If your citation frequency is strong on ChatGPT but low on Perplexity, the diagnostic path is different from the reverse. Perplexity relies heavily on live web retrieval, so low Perplexity citation often points to content structure issues — pages that are not well-suited to extraction by retrieval-augmented generation systems. Low ChatGPT citation without web browsing enabled may point to entity recognition gaps — your brand is not sufficiently established in the training data that the model draws on when generating responses without live retrieval.</p>
        <p>Week-on-week volatility is normal in GEO tracking data because AI responses are inherently probabilistic. Do not act on a single week's movement in either direction. Look for sustained trends over three to four weeks before drawing conclusions or making significant strategy adjustments. The exception is a sudden, steep drop (more than 15 percentage points in a single week) — this warrants immediate investigation, as it may indicate a platform update, a crawl issue affecting your cited pages, or a competitor intervention that needs an urgent response.</p>
        <p>For guidance on building the metrics framework that governs how you interpret and report tracking data, see our guide on <a href="/how-to-measure-geo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">how to measure GEO</a> performance. For the broader strategic context in which GEO tracking sits, the <a href="/geo-monitoring/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO monitoring hub</a> covers the full picture — from initial audits through to stakeholder reporting.</p>
      </section>

